[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference derives the posterior probability as a consequence of two antecedents: a prior probability and a "likelihood function" derived from a statistical model for the observed data.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If that term is approximately 1, then the probability of the hypothesis given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ , is about ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ , about 50% likely - equally likely or not likely.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If that term is very small, close to zero, then the probability of the hypothesis, given the evidence, $P(H\mid E)$ is close to 1 or the conditional hypothesis is quite likely.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If that term is very large, much larger than 1, then the hypothesis, given the evidence, is quite unlikely.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian updating is widely used and computationally convenient.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] However, it is not the only updating rule that might be considered rational.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Ian Hacking noted that traditional "Dutch book" arguments did not specify Bayesian updating: they left open the possibility that non-Bayesian updating rules could avoid Dutch books.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Hacking wrote: "And neither the Dutch book argument nor any other in the personalist arsenal of proofs of the probability axioms entails the dynamic assumption.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] So the personalist requires the dynamic assumption to be Bayesian.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is true that in consistency a personalist could abandon the Bayesian model of learning from experience.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Indeed, there are non-Bayesian updating rules that also avoid Dutch books (as discussed in the literature on "probability kinematics") following the publication of Richard C.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Jeffrey's rule, which applies Bayes' rule to the case where the evidence itself is assigned a probability.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The additional hypotheses needed to uniquely require Bayesian updating have been deemed to be substantial, complicated, and unsatisfactory.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If evidence is simultaneously used to update belief over a set of exclusive and exhaustive propositions, Bayesian inference may be thought of as acting on this belief distribution as a whole.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Suppose a process is generating independent and identically distributed events $E_{n},\ n=1,2,3,\ldots$ , but the probability distribution is unknown.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Let the event space $\Omega$ represent the current state of belief for this process.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Each model is represented by event $M_{m}$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The conditional probabilities $P(E_{n}\mid M_{m})$ are specified to define the models. $P(M_{m})$ is the degree of belief in $M_{m}$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Before the first inference step, $\{P(M_{m})\}$ is a set of *initial prior probabilities*.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] These must sum to 1, but are otherwise arbitrary.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Suppose that the process is observed to generate $E\in \{E_{n}\}$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] For each $M\in \{M_{m}\}$ , the prior $P(M)$ is updated to the posterior $P(M\mid E)$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Upon observation of further evidence, this procedure may be repeated.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] By parameterizing the space of models, the belief in all models may be updated in a single step.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The distribution of belief over the model space may then be thought of as a distribution of belief over the parameter space.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The distributions in this section are expressed as continuous, represented by probability densities, as this is the usual situation.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The technique is, however, equally applicable to discrete distributions.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Let the vector ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ span the parameter space.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Let the initial prior distribution over ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ be $p({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\alpha }})$ , where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ is a set of parameters to the prior itself, or *hyperparameters*.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Let $\mathbf {E} =(e_{1},\dots ,e_{n})$ be a sequence of independent and identically distributed event observations, where all $e_{i}$ are distributed as $p(e\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ for some ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This is expressed in words as "posterior is proportional to likelihood times prior", or sometimes as "posterior = likelihood times prior, over evidence".
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] $P_{X}^{y}(A)=E(1_{A}(X)|Y=y)$ Existence and uniqueness of the needed conditional expectation is a consequence of the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This was formulated by Kolmogorov in his famous book from 1933.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Kolmogorov underlines the importance of conditional probability by writing "I wish to call attention to ... and especially the theory of conditional probabilities and conditional expectations ..." in the Preface.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The Bayes theorem determines the posterior distribution from the prior distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Uniqueness requires continuity assumptions.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayes' theorem can be generalized to include improper prior distributions such as the uniform distribution on the real line.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Modern Markov chain Monte Carlo methods have boosted the importance of Bayes' theorem including cases with improper priors.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian theory calls for the use of the posterior predictive distribution to do predictive inference, i.e., to predict the distribution of a new, unobserved data point.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] That is, instead of a fixed point as a prediction, a distribution over possible points is returned.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Only this way is the entire posterior distribution of the parameter(s) used.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] By comparison, prediction in frequentist statistics often involves finding an optimum point estimate of the parameter(s)—e.g., by maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori estimation (MAP)—and then plugging this estimate into the formula for the distribution of a data point.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This has the disadvantage that it does not account for any uncertainty in the value of the parameter, and hence will underestimate the variance of the predictive distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In some instances, frequentist statistics can work around this problem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] For example, confidence intervals and prediction intervals in frequentist statistics when constructed from a normal distribution with unknown mean and variance are constructed using a Student's t-distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian statistics, however, the posterior predictive distribution can always be determined exactly—or at least to an arbitrary level of precision when numerical methods are used.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Both types of predictive distributions have the form of a compound probability distribution (as does the marginal likelihood).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In fact, if the prior distribution is a conjugate prior, such that the prior and posterior distributions come from the same family, it can be seen that both prior and posterior predictive distributions also come from the same family of compound distributions.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] That is, if the model were true, the evidence would be more likely than is predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The reverse applies for a decrease in belief.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If the belief does not change, ${\textstyle {\frac {P(E\mid M)}{P(E)}}=1\Rightarrow P(E\mid M)=P(E)}$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] That is, the evidence is independent of the model.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If the model were true, the evidence would be exactly as likely as predicted by the current state of belief.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This can be interpreted to mean that hard convictions are insensitive to counter-evidence.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The former follows directly from Bayes' theorem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The latter can be derived by applying the first rule to the event "not M " in place of " M ", yielding "if $1-P(M)=0$ , then $1-P(M\mid E)=0$ ", from which the result immediately follows.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Consider the behaviour of a belief distribution as it is updated a large number of times with independent and identically distributed trials.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] For sufficiently nice prior probabilities, the Bernstein-von Mises theorem gives that in the limit of infinite trials, the posterior converges to a Gaussian distribution independent of the initial prior under some conditions firstly outlined and rigorously proven by Joseph L.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Doob in 1948, namely if the random variable in consideration has a finite probability space.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The more general results were obtained later by the statistician David A.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Freedman who published in two seminal research papers in 1963 and 1965 when and under what circumstances the asymptotic behaviour of posterior is guaranteed.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] His 1963 paper treats, like Doob (1949), the finite case and comes to a satisfactory conclusion.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] However, if the random variable has an infinite but countable probability space (i.e., corresponding to a die with infinite many faces) the 1965 paper demonstrates that for a dense subset of priors the Bernstein-von Mises theorem is not applicable.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In this case there is almost surely no asymptotic convergence.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Later in the 1980s and 1990s Freedman and Persi Diaconis continued to work on the case of infinite countable probability spaces.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] To summarise, there may be insufficient trials to suppress the effects of the initial choice, and especially for large (but finite) systems the convergence might be very slow.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In parameterized form, the prior distribution is often assumed to come from a family of distributions called conjugate priors.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The usefulness of a conjugate prior is that the corresponding posterior distribution will be in the same family, and the calculation may be expressed in closed form.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is often desired to use a posterior distribution to estimate a parameter or variable.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Several methods of Bayesian estimation select measurements of central tendency from the posterior distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] For one-dimensional problems, a unique median exists for practical continuous problems.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The posterior median is attractive as a robust estimator.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] There are examples where no maximum is attained, in which case the set of MAP estimates is empty.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] There are other methods of estimation that minimize the posterior risk (expected-posterior loss) with respect to a loss function, and these are of interest to statistical decision theory using the sampling distribution (frequentist statistics).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Suppose there are two full bowls of cookies.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bowl #1 has 10 chocolate chip and 30 plain cookies, while bowl #2 has 20 of each.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Fred picks a bowl at random and then picks a cookie at random, which means that there is no reason to believe Fred treats one bowl differently from another, likewise for the cookies.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] As to how probable it is that Fred picked it out of bowl #1, that is an example of a Bayesian inference-approachable problem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Intuitively, it seems clear that the answer should be more than a half, since there are more plain cookies in bowl #1.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The precise answer is given by Bayes' theorem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is given that the bowls are identical from Fred's point of view, thus $P(H_{1})=P(H_{2})$ , and the two must add up to 1, so both are equal to 0.5.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The event E is the observation of a plain cookie.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] An archaeologist is working at a site thought to be from the medieval period, between the 11th century to the 16th century.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] However, it is uncertain exactly when in this period the site was inhabited.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Fragments of pottery are found, some of which are glazed and some of which are decorated.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is expected that if the site were inhabited during the early medieval period, then 1% of the pottery would be glazed and 50% of its area decorated, whereas if it had been inhabited in the late medieval period then 81% would be glazed and 5% of its area decorated.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] How confident can the archaeologist be in the date of inhabitation as fragments are unearthed?
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The degree of belief in the continuous variable C (century) is to be calculated, with the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ as evidence.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] When a new fragment of type e is discovered, that means *more information* for the investigation and, through Bayes' theorem, an *updated* Bayesian inference towards an improved degree of belief (or confidence) in the archeologists' estimation.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] A computer simulation of the changing belief as 50 fragments are unearthed is shown on the graph.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the simulation, the site was inhabited around 1420, or $c=15.2$ .
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The Bernstein-von Mises theorem asserts here the asymptotic convergence to the "true" distribution because the probability space corresponding to the discrete set of events $\{GD,G{\bar {D}},{\bar {G}}D,{\bar {G}}{\bar {D}}\}$ is finite (see above section on asymptotic behaviour of the posterior).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] A decision-theoretic justification of the use of Bayesian inference was given by Abraham Wald, who proved that every unique Bayesian procedure is admissible.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Conversely, every admissible statistical procedure is either a Bayesian procedure or a limit of Bayesian procedures.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Wald characterized admissible procedures as Bayesian procedures (and limits of Bayesian procedures), making the Bayesian formalism a central technique in such areas of frequentist inference as parameter estimation, hypothesis testing, and computing confidence intervals.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian methodology also plays a role in model selection where the aim is to select one model from a set of competing models that represents most closely the underlying process that generated the observed data.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In Bayesian model comparison, the model with the highest posterior probability given the data is selected.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The posterior probability of a model depends on the evidence, or marginal likelihood, which reflects the probability that the data is generated by the model, and on the prior belief of the model.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] When two competing models are a priori considered to be equiprobable, the ratio of their posterior probabilities corresponds to the Bayes factor.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Since Bayesian model comparison is aimed on selecting the model with the highest posterior probability, this methodology is also referred to as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) selection rule or the MAP probability rule.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] While conceptually simple, Bayesian methods can be mathematically and numerically challenging.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Probabilistic programming languages (PPLs) implement functions to easily build Bayesian models together with efficient automatic inference methods.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This helps separate the model building from the inference, allowing practitioners to focus on their specific problems and leaving PPLs to handle the computational details for them.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] See the separate Wikipedia entry on Bayesian statistics, specifically the statistical modeling section in that page.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has applications in artificial intelligence and expert systems.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference techniques have been a fundamental part of computerized pattern recognition techniques since the late 1950s.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Recently Bayesian inference has gained popularity among the phylogenetics community for these reasons; a number of applications allow many demographic and evolutionary parameters to be estimated simultaneously.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] As applied to statistical classification, Bayesian inference has been used to develop algorithms for identifying e-mail spam.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Applications which make use of Bayesian inference for spam filtering include CRM114, DSPAM, Bogofilter, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Mozilla, XEAMS, and others.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Spam classification is treated in more detail in the article on the naïve Bayes classifier.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's Inductive inference is the theory of prediction based on observations; for example, predicting the next symbol based upon a given series of symbols.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The only assumption is that the environment follows some unknown but computable probability distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is a formal inductive framework that combines two well-studied principles of inductive inference: Bayesian statistics and Occam's Razor.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Solomonoff's universal prior probability of any prefix *p* of a computable sequence *x* is the sum of the probabilities of all programs (for a universal computer) that compute something starting with *p*.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Given some *p* and any computable but unknown probability distribution from which *x* is sampled, the universal prior and Bayes' theorem can be used to predict the yet unseen parts of *x* in optimal fashion.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference has been applied in different bioinformatics applications, including differential gene expression analysis.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference is also used in a general cancer risk model, called CIRI (Continuous Individualized Risk Index), where serial measurements are incorporated to update a Bayesian model which is primarily built from prior knowledge.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In cosmology, it is often employed with computational techniques such as Markov chain Monte Carlo(MCMC) and Nested sampling algorithm to analyse complex datasets and navigate high-dimensional parameter space.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] A notable application is to the Planck 2018 CMB data for parameter inference.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The six base cosmological parameters in Lambda-CDM model are not predicted by a theory, but rather fitted from Cosmic microwave background (CMB) data to a chosen model of cosmology (the Lambda-CDM model).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The bayesian code for cosmology `cobaya` sets up cosmological runs and interfaces cosmological likelihoods, Boltzmann code, which computes the predicted CMB anisotropies for any given set of cosmological parameters, with MCMC or nested sampler.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This computational framework is not limited to the standard model, it is also essential for testing alternative or extended theories of cosmology, such as theories with early dark energy, or modified gravity theories introducing additional parameters beyond Lambda-CDM.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian model comparison can then be employed to calculate the evidence for competing models, providing a statistical basis to assess whether the data support them over the standard Lambda-CDM.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian inference can be used by jurors to coherently accumulate the evidence for and against a defendant, and to see whether, in totality, it meets their personal threshold for "beyond a reasonable doubt".
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayes' theorem is applied successively to all evidence presented, with the posterior from one stage becoming the prior for the next.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The benefit of a Bayesian approach is that it gives the juror an unbiased, rational mechanism for combining evidence.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It may be appropriate to explain Bayes' theorem to jurors in odds form, as betting odds are more widely understood than probabilities.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Alternatively, a logarithmic approach, replacing multiplication with addition, might be easier for a jury to handle.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] If the existence of the crime is not in doubt, only the identity of the culprit, it has been suggested that the prior should be uniform over the qualifying population.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] For example, if 1,000 people could have committed the crime, the prior probability of guilt would be 1/1000.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The use of Bayes' theorem by jurors is controversial.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the United Kingdom, a defence expert witness explained Bayes' theorem to the jury in *R v Adams*.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The jury convicted, but the case went to appeal on the basis that no means of accumulating evidence had been provided for jurors who did not wish to use Bayes' theorem.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the criterion on which a verdict in a criminal trial should be based is *not* the probability of guilt, but rather the *probability of the evidence, given that the defendant is innocent* (akin to a frequentist p-value).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] He argues that if the posterior probability of guilt is to be computed by Bayes' theorem, the prior probability of guilt must be known.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] This will depend on the incidence of the crime, which is an unusual piece of evidence to consider in a criminal trial.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is guilty.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] – the known facts and testimony could have arisen if the defendant is innocent.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Gardner-Medwin argues that the jury should believe both *A* and not-*B* in order to convict.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] *A* and not-*B* implies the truth of *C*, but the reverse is not true.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] It is possible that *B* and *C* are both true, but in this case he argues that a jury should acquit, even though they know that they will be letting some guilty people go free.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Bayesian epistemology is a movement that advocates for Bayesian inference as a means of justifying the rules of inductive logic.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Karl Popper and David Miller have rejected the idea of Bayesian rationalism, i.e. using Bayes rule to make epistemological inferences: It is prone to the same vicious circle as any other justificationist epistemology, because it presupposes what it attempts to justify.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The problem considered by Bayes in Proposition 9 of his essay, "An Essay Towards Solving a Problem in the Doctrine of Chances", is the posterior distribution for the parameter *a* (the success rate) of the binomial distribution.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] The term 'Bayesian' refers to Thomas Bayes (1701–1761), who proved that probabilistic limits could be placed on an unknown event.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] However, it was Pierre-Simon Laplace (1749–1827) who introduced (as Principle VI) what is now called Bayes' theorem and used it to address problems in celestial mechanics, medical statistics, reliability, and jurisprudence.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Early Bayesian inference, which used uniform priors following Laplace's principle of insufficient reason, was called inverse probability (because it infers backwards from observations to parameters, or from effects to causes).
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] After the 1920s, inverse probability was largely supplanted by a collection of methods that came to be called frequentist statistics.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the 20th century, the ideas of Laplace were further developed in two different directions, giving rise to *objective* and *subjective* currents in Bayesian practice.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the objective (or "non-informative") current, the statistical analysis depends only on the model assumed, the data analyzed, and the method assigning the prior, which differs from one objective Bayesian practitioner to another.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the subjective (or "informative") current, the specification of the prior depends on the belief—the propositions on which the analysis is prepared to act—which can summarize information from experts, previous studies, etc.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] In the 1980s, there was a dramatic growth in research and applications of Bayesian methods, mostly attributed to the discovery of Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, which removed many of the computational problems, and an increasing interest in nonstandard, complex applications.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Despite growth of Bayesian research, most undergraduate teaching is still based on frequentist statistics.
[src:stan-language/bayesian-inference] Nonetheless, Bayesian methods are widely accepted and used, such as for example in the field of machine learning.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The **Hamiltonian Monte Carlo** algorithm (originally known as **hybrid Monte Carlo**) is a Markov chain Monte Carlo method for obtaining a sequence of random samples whose distribution converges to a target probability distribution that is difficult to sample directly.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This sequence can be used to estimate integrals of the target distribution, such as expected values and moments.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Hamiltonian Monte Carlo corresponds to an instance of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, with a Hamiltonian dynamics evolution simulated using a time-reversible and volume-preserving numerical integrator (typically the leapfrog integrator) to propose a move to a new point in the state space.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The reduced correlation means fewer Markov chain samples are needed to approximate integrals with respect to the target probability distribution for a given Monte Carlo error.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm was originally proposed by Simon Duane, Anthony Kennedy, Brian Pendleton and Duncan Roweth in 1987 for calculations in lattice quantum chromodynamics.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Neal showed how the method could be used for a broader class of statistical problems, in particular artificial neural networks.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] But the burden of having to provide the algorithm with gradients of the model graph delayed its wider adoption in statistics and other quantitative disciplines, until in the mid-2010s the developers of Stan implemented HMC in combination with automatic differentiation.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the target distribution to sample is $f(\mathbf {x} )$ for $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ ( $d\geq 1$ ) and a chain of samples $\mathbf {X} _{0},\mathbf {X} _{1},\mathbf {X} _{2},\ldots$ is required.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $x_{i}$ and $p_{i}$ are the i th component of the position and momentum vector respectively and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $U(\mathbf {x} )$ is the potential energy.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] which comes from the Boltzmann's factor.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Note that the Hamiltonian H is dimensionless in this formulation because the exponential probability weight $\exp \left(-H\right)$ has to be well defined.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in simulations at finite temperature T the factor $k_{\text{B}}T$ (with the Boltzmann constant $k_{\text{B}}$ ) is directly absorbed into U and M .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm requires a positive integer for number of leapfrog steps L and a positive number for the step size $\Delta t$ .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the chain is at $\mathbf {X} _{n}=\mathbf {x} _{n}$ .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] First, a random Gaussian momentum $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ is drawn from ${\text{N}}\left(\mathbf {0} ,M\right)$ .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Next, the particle will run under Hamiltonian dynamics for time $L\Delta t$ , this is done by solving the Hamilton's equations numerically using the leapfrog algorithm.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] These equations are to be applied to $\mathbf {x} _{n}(0)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ L times to obtain $\mathbf {x} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The leapfrog algorithm is an approximate solution to the motion of non-interacting classical particles.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] If exact, the solution will never change the initial randomly-generated energy distribution, as energy is conserved for each particle in the presence of a classical potential energy field.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In order to reach a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution, particles must have some sort of interaction with, for example, a surrounding heat bath, so that the entire system can take on different energies with probabilities according to the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] One way to move the system towards a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution is to change the state of the particles using the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] So first, one applies the leapfrog step, then a Metropolis-Hastings step.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] A full update consists of first randomly sampling the momenta $\mathbf {p}$ (independently of the previous iterations), then integrating the equations of motion (e.g. with leapfrog), and finally obtaining the new configuration from the Metropolis-Hastings accept/reject step.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This updating mechanism is repeated to obtain $\mathbf {X} _{n+1},\mathbf {X} _{n+2},\mathbf {X} _{n+3},\ldots$ .
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The No U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) is an extension by controlling the number of steps L automatically.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the one dimensional ${\text{N}}(0,1/{\sqrt {k}})$ case, the potential is $U(x)=kx^{2}/2$ which corresponds to the potential of a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too large, the particle will oscillate and thus waste computational time.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too small, the particle will behave like a random walk.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Loosely, NUTS runs the Hamiltonian dynamics both forwards and backwards in time randomly until a U-Turn condition is satisfied.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] When that happens, a random point from the path is chosen for the MCMC sample and the process is repeated from that new point.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In detail, a binary tree is constructed to trace the path of the leap frog steps.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] To produce a MCMC sample, an iterative procedure is conducted.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Let $\mathbf {x} _{n}^{+}$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}^{+}$ be the position and momentum of the forward particle respectively.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In each iteration, the binary tree selects at random uniformly to move the forward particle forwards in time or the backward particle backwards in time.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Also for each iteration, the number of leap frog steps increase by a factor of 2.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the first iteration, the forward particle moves forwards in time using 1 leap frog step.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In the next iteration, the backward particle moves backwards in time using 2 leap frog steps.
[src:stan-language/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This is usually satisfied if the remaining HMC parameters are sensible.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:stan-language/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] The **posterior probability** is a type of conditional probability that results from updating the prior probability with information summarized by the likelihood via an application of Bayes' rule.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] From an epistemological perspective, the posterior probability contains everything there is to know about an uncertain proposition (such as a scientific hypothesis, or parameter values), given prior knowledge and a mathematical model describing the observations available at a particular time.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] After the arrival of new information, the current posterior probability may serve as the prior in another round of Bayesian updating.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] In the context of Bayesian statistics, the **posterior probability distribution** usually describes the epistemic uncertainty about statistical parameters conditional on a collection of observed data.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] From a given posterior distribution, various point and interval estimates can be derived, such as the maximum a posteriori (MAP) or the highest posterior density interval (HPDI).
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] But while conceptually simple, the posterior distribution is generally not tractable and therefore needs to be either analytically or numerically approximated.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] In Bayesian statistics, the posterior probability is the probability distribution of the parameters $\theta$ given the evidence X , and is denoted $p(\theta |X)$ .
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] It contrasts with the likelihood function, which is the probability of the evidence given the parameters: $p(X|\theta )$ .
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] for continuous $\theta$ , or by summing $p(x|\theta )p(\theta )$ over all possible values of $\theta$ for discrete $\theta$ .
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] The posterior probability is therefore proportional to the product *Likelihood · Prior probability*.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] Suppose there is a school with 60% boys and 40% girls as students.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] The girls wear trousers or skirts in equal numbers; all boys wear trousers.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] An observer sees a (random) student from a distance; all the observer can see is that this student is wearing trousers.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] What is the probability this student is a girl?
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] The correct answer can be computed using Bayes' theorem.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] The event G is that the student observed is a girl, and the event T is that the student observed is wearing trousers.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] An intuitive way to solve this is to assume the school has *N* students.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] Number of boys = 0.6*N* and number of girls = 0.4*N*.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] If *N* is large enough that rounding errors can be ignored, total number of trouser wearers = 0.6*N* + 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] And number of girl trouser wearers = 50% of 0.4*N*.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] In other words, if you separated out the group of trouser wearers, a quarter of that group will be girls.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] Therefore, if you see trousers, the most you can deduce is that you are looking at a single sample from a subset of students where 25% are girls.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] And by definition, chance of this random student being a girl is 25%.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] Every Bayes-theorem problem can be solved in this way.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] Posterior probability is a conditional probability conditioned on randomly observed data.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] For a random variable, it is important to summarize its amount of uncertainty.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] One way to achieve this goal is to provide a credible interval of the posterior probability.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] In classification, posterior probabilities reflect the uncertainty of assessing an observation to particular class, see also class-membership probabilities.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] While statistical classification methods by definition generate posterior probabilities, Machine Learners usually supply membership values which do not induce any probabilistic confidence.
[src:stan-language/posterior-probability] It is desirable to transform or rescale membership values to class-membership probabilities, since they are comparable and additionally more easily applicable for post-processing.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Probabilistic reasoning has been used for a wide variety of tasks such as predicting stock prices, recommending movies, diagnosing computers, detecting cyber intrusions and image detection.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] However, until recently (partially due to limited computing power), probabilistic programming was limited in scope, and most inference algorithms had to be written manually for each task.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Nevertheless, in 2015, a 50-line probabilistic computer vision program was used to generate 3D models of human faces based on 2D images of those faces.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] The program used inverse graphics as the basis of its inference method, and was built using the Picture package in Julia.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] This made possible "in 50 lines of code what used to take thousands".
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] The Gen probabilistic programming library (also written in Julia) has been applied to vision and robotics tasks.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] More recently, the probabilistic programming system Turing.jl has been applied in various pharmaceutical and economics applications.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Probabilistic programming in Julia has also been combined with differentiable programming by combining the Julia package Zygote.jl with Turing.jl.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Probabilistic programming languages are also commonly used in Bayesian cognitive science to develop and evaluate models of cognition.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] PPLs often extend from a basic language.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] For instance, Turing.jl is based on Julia, Infer.NET is based on .NET Framework, while PRISM extends from Prolog.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] However, some PPLs, such as WinBUGS, offer a self-contained language that maps closely to the mathematical representation of the statistical models, with no obvious origin in another programming language.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] The language for WinBUGS was implemented to perform Bayesian computation using Gibbs Sampling and related algorithms.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Although implemented in a relatively unknown programming language (Component Pascal), this language permits Bayesian inference for a wide variety of statistical models using a flexible computational approach.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] More recently, other languages to support Bayesian model specification and inference allow different or more efficient choices for the underlying Bayesian computation, and are accessible from the R data analysis and programming environment, e.g.: Stan, NIMBLE and NUTS.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] The influence of the BUGS language is evident in these later languages, which even use the same syntax for some aspects of model specification.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Several PPLs are in active development, including some in beta test.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] A **probabilistic relational programming language** (PRPL) is a PPL specially designed to describe and infer with probabilistic relational models (PRMs).
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] A PRM is usually developed with a set of algorithms for reducing, inference about and discovery of concerned distributions, which are embedded into the corresponding PRPL.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Probabilistic logic programming is a programming paradigm that extends logic programming with probabilities.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] Most approaches to probabilistic logic programming are based on the *distribution semantics,* which splits a program into a set of probabilistic facts and a logic program.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] It defines a probability distribution on interpretations of the Herbrand universe of the program.
[src:stan-language/probabilistic-programming] This list summarises the variety of PPLs that are currently available, and clarifies their origins.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan is licensed under the New BSD License.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan is named in honour of Stanislaw Ulam, pioneer of the Monte Carlo method.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan was created by a development team consisting of 52 members that includes Andrew Gelman, Bob Carpenter, Daniel Lee, Ben Goodrich, and others.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] A simple linear regression model can be described as $y_{n}=\alpha +\beta x_{n}+\epsilon _{n}$ , where $\epsilon _{n}\sim {\text{normal}}(0,\sigma )$ .
[src:stan-language/stan-software] This can also be expressed as $y_{n}\sim {\text{normal}}(\alpha +\beta X_{n},\sigma )$ .
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan implements gradient-based Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithms for Bayesian inference, stochastic, gradient-based variational Bayesian methods for approximate Bayesian inference, and gradient-based optimization for penalized maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan implements reverse-mode automatic differentiation to calculate gradients of the model, which is required by HMC, NUTS, L-BFGS, BFGS, and variational inference.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] The automatic differentiation within Stan can be used outside of the probabilistic programming language.
[src:stan-language/stan-software] Stan is used in fields including social science, pharmaceutical statistics, market research, and medical imaging.
